title: Calgary’s Mayoral Race: A Toss-Up with No Clear Winner....Yet
content:
Calgary’s municipal election is heating up — and the latest numbers show it’s anybody’s game. While incumbent Jyoti Gondek holds a slight lead in the polls, the real frontrunner right now is uncertainty.

Here’s where the candidates stand:

  • Jyoti Gondek: 15%

  • Jeromy Farkas: 14%

  • Sonya Sharp: 8%

  • Jeff Davison: 6%

  • Brian Thiessen: 3%

  • Undecided voters: a whopping 45%

That undecided block is the biggest wildcard. Even among those most likely to vote, 41% haven’t made up their minds — which means momentum over the next few weeks could shift everything.

Who Has the Edge?

Right now, Gondek and Farkas are essentially tied. Gondek benefits from name recognition (74% awareness) and leads among residents who think the city is headed in the right direction. But that group only makes up one-third of Calgarians. The majority — 57% — say Calgary is on the wrong track. And among them, Farkas leads.

Farkas also scores the highest approval rating (49%) among voters who know him, just ahead of Sharp (48%) and Davison (47%). Gondek trails at 37%.

Who’s Showing Up?

The voter base leans older and wealthier:

  • 87% of voters aged 55+ say they’re likely to vote

  • 70% of those earning over $100k say they’ll definitely vote

Gondek performs best among those who think Calgary is doing well — but that’s not the dominant mood. Farkas gains ground with the frustrated majority.

What Matters to Voters?

The top issues heading into October:

  1. Lowering taxes (43%)

  2. Fiscal restraint (25%)

  3. Reducing poverty (23%)

Voters are watching for candidates who can speak to both economic discipline and social responsibility — a tricky balance.

The Bottom Line

Calgary’s mayoral race is wide open. Gondek and Farkas are neck and neck, but with nearly half the electorate still undecided, this election will be decided not just by who leads now — but by who can lock in support over the next six weeks.

The question isn’t who’s winning today — it’s who can seize the moment.
excerpt: The August 2025 municipal poll from Leger offers a clear message: Calgary’s electorate is restless, fragmented, and still very much in play. While Mayor Jyoti Gondek holds a razor-thin lead in voting intention (15%), former councillor Jeromy Farkas (14%) is statistically tied — and arguably better positioned to gain ground among the city’s most motivated voters.

title: Municipal Elections in Alberta Are Coming — and So Are Well‑Paid Temporary Jobs $$
content:
Alberta’s municipal elections are coming up this October, and while most of us think about casting our votes, there’s something else happening behind the scenes: municipalities across the province are hiring.

These are short-term jobs that pay well, don’t require political experience, and give you a front-row seat to how local democracy works.

Whether you’re a student, between jobs, semi-retired, or just want to earn a little extra, this is a solid opportunity to get involved in your community—and get paid doing it.

What kind of work are we talking about?

Every town and city is a bit different, but most are looking for:

  • Election day staff (like Deputy Returning Officers and registration clerks)

  • Advance poll workers

  • Ballot counters

  • Site supervisors or troubleshooters

Pay typically ranges from $20–$30/hour, with training paid separately. Some positions offer a flat daily rate ($250–$400), depending on your role and responsibilities.

Where to Apply

Here are just a few examples of places hiring right now:

  • Elections Alberta – Province-wide roles. You can apply as young as 16.

  • Calgary – Hiring around 4,500 workers. Applications open August 27.

  • Edmonton – Over 5,000 spots available for advance voting and election day.

  • Lethbridge – Roles pay $150 to $400/day depending on the job. Deadline: Sept 9.

  • Banff – Hiring for $27/hour. Training starts in early October.

  • Sturgeon County – Paying $26–$30/hour with mileage and phone allowance.

  • Clearwater County – Work advance voting (Oct 6) or Election Day (Oct 20).

  • Smoky Lake County – Workers needed, training required on Oct 7 or 14.

  • Leduc – Multiple positions open, including standby staff.

  • Why This Matters

These elections decide who runs your city or town for the next four years—mayors, councillors, school board trustees. The work might only last a few days, but it's crucial. And honestly, it’s one of the easier ways to contribute to your community while picking up some well-earned cash.

What You Need to Know

  • Most jobs are first-come, first-served

  • You must be at least 18 years old (some accept 16+)

  • You’ll likely have to commit to a full-day shift on election day

  • Training is required—but it's usually online or in-person a few days before

If you’re interested, don’t wait. Jobs are filling up, and every town’s deadline is a little different.

This is a great way to learn something new, meet people in your community, and get paid for stepping up.

Want us to spotlight your local election office or job board? Drop us a line.
excerpt: Municipal elections across Alberta are kicking off this October—and many communities are actively hiring election workers. These short-term gigs pay well, offer solid hours, and come with training. Whether you want to earn extra cash, up your résumé, or help your community, this is your moment.

title: Calgary Rent Prices Are Finally Cooling—Here’s What the Numbers Reveal
content:
Calgary Rent Prices Are Finally Cooling—Here’s What the Numbers Reveal - https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=H6abGCI8IJU

For the first time in months, Calgary renters are getting a little breathing room. Let’s dive into the data—and what it all means for people calling this city home.

What the Data Shows

A 9% drop in average rent in July brought Calgary’s monthly rate to $1,914. That’s one of the steepest declines in Canada—even compared to Vancouver, which clocked in at a slightly higher 10% drop with average rent near $2,803.

Three-bedroom units took the biggest hit, dropping 15% year-over-year to about $2,387.

Nationally, average rents slid 3.6% in July, marking the tenth straight month of decline. Still, prices sit well above pre-pandemic levels—11.1% higher than three years ago.

Locally, Zumper reports a 6% drop in annual median rent, landing at $1,867 in August—about 7% below the national median.

Yet, Apartments.com data shows Calgary’s average rent at $1,669/month, reflecting a 2.3% annual decrease.

Taken together, these numbers paint a picture of a slowing but still elevated rental market.

 ![Canada Rent](/images/Canada Rent.jpg)
 
Trends in Focus

Calgary is among just three major Canadian cities (alongside Vancouver and Toronto) to show multi-year declines—6% over two years, despite overall long-term gains.

Meanwhile, Edmonton and Ottawa continue to see rent increases, highlighting a widening regional split.

The steep drop in three-bedroom units suggests shifting tenant demand—perhaps a shift to smaller spaces or different housing types.

The market might be rebalancing, but affordability is still fragile, especially with demand rebounding and in-migration returning.

Cultural Impact: Why Rent Trends Matter

This isn’t just a stats story—it’s about real people, communities, and creative corners of Calgary:

Artists, startups, and grassroots groups: Slower rent increases could mean more rehearsal space, storefronts, and cultural hubs staying afloat.

Neighborhood vitality: As rents ease, mixed-income communities can sustain local cafés, independent venues, and cultural festivity—without getting priced out.

Community rebuilding: After a period marked by rising costs, this cooldown could boost neighborhood cohesion, inclusivity, and long-term creative investment.

What’s Next?

Watch the fall: With seasonally slower rental cycles ahead, prices may dip further—or stabilize. The pattern of consistent declines suggests a broader cooling, not just a short-term blip.

Keep an eye on housing supply: If downtown conversions and new rental developments continue, that could fuel further easing. But an influx of renters or limited supply might push prices back up.

Policy matters: Supportive housing policy, incentives for cultural spaces, or targeted affordability measures could shape how this trend evolves.

Calgary's rental market is shifting—and while that signals hope for affordability, it’s also a reminder that housing and culture are intertwined. When rents ease, creativity can thrive. When they rise, cultural life often shrinks. This cooldown might be more than a financial reprieve—it could be a moment when the city gets a little more room to breathe, create, and grow.
excerpt: For the first time in months, Calgary renters are getting a little breathing room. Let’s dive into the data—and what it all means for people calling this city home.

title: Best Sushi in Calgary
content:
1. Eight – Canada’s VIP Table
Imagine an eight-seat hidden boîte where Canada’s top chefs or visiting culinary legends host intimate dinners—and you’ve found Eight. It’s not just a restaurant; it’s a secret society of gastronomic genius, perched at #6 on Canada’s 100 Best Restaurants list.

2. Nupo – Omakase Goes Plant-Powered
The younger, plant-forward sibling to Shokunin, Nupo offers a veggie-driven omakase that’s as inventive as it is delicious. Not only did it land at #30 on the list, but it also turns sushi into an art form.

3. River Café – Dining in Nature’s Own Living Room
Nestled amidst trees on Prince’s Island Park, River Café offers a romantic escape from the city hustle—with menus that shift with the seasons and landscapes. It made its mark at #47.
Daily Hive
Tourism Calgary

4. DOPO – The New Italian Sensation
This Italian-inspired newcomer opened its doors in late 2024 and didn’t just ruffle feathers—it soared to #56 on Canada’s 100 Best Restaurants list and snagged a spot on the Best New Restaurants roster. Grazie, DOPO!


5. Shokunin – The Omakase OG of YYC
Since 2016, Shokunin has set Calgary’s izakaya and omakase scene on fire, thanks to chef Darren MacLean’s daring creativity—yakitori, innovative yakitori, and yes… even that infamous chicken ass. It ranks at #74, and there’s no forgetting it.


A Dash of “Also-Ran” Stardust
But wait—Calgary’s got more gusto than just its “best of” list! Here are a few other mouthwatering mentions that make the scene so sizzling:

Major Tom – Dining literally on top of the world (the 40th floor!) with jaw-dropping views and the infamous “Major Tots.” Iconic views = iconic bites.

Whether you want to whisper "chef’s kiss" to your meal at Eight, linger in a riverside moment at River Café, or blast your taste buds into orbit at Shokunin, this city’s dining scene is dishing dynamite experiences.

So, book your reservations — or just show up starstruck — because Calgary’s food scene isn’t just good, it’s famous.

title: Calgary’s Green Line: Transforming Transit and Connecting Communities
content:
Calgary is on track to deliver one of the most transformative infrastructure projects in its history — the Green Line Light Rail Transit (LRT). Designed as a modern, efficient, and sustainable transit solution, the Green Line will connect underserved communities, reduce traffic congestion, and create new opportunities for economic growth.

Phase 1 of the project, currently underway, will extend from Shepard in the southeast to Eau Claire in the downtown core, covering approximately 18 kilometres. This segment includes key stations such as Ogden, Ramsay/Inglewood, and the Beltline, linking residential neighborhoods to major employment and cultural hubs.

The Green Line is more than just a transportation upgrade — it is a city-building initiative. The project’s design incorporates urban renewal features, such as pedestrian-friendly streetscapes, public art installations, and enhanced green spaces. It also aligns with Calgary’s climate goals by encouraging transit use over car travel, thereby cutting greenhouse gas emissions.

Economic benefits are significant as well. The Green Line is expected to generate thousands of construction jobs and stimulate development along its corridor, attracting businesses and housing projects to areas with improved accessibility.

Once completed, the Green Line will become the backbone of Calgary’s LRT network, seamlessly integrating with existing Red and Blue lines. Future phases are planned to extend the route north to Keystone Hills, ultimately creating a 46-kilometre line that serves nearly a quarter of Calgary’s population.

As construction progresses, the Green Line stands as a symbol of Calgary’s commitment to building a more connected, sustainable, and livable city for generations to come.
excerpt: The Green Line is Calgary’s most ambitious public transit project to date, promising to reshape how the city moves. Spanning multiple communities, this LRT expansion will boost connectivity, cut commute times, and support Calgary’s long-term growth.
author: James Johnson

title: Calgary's Evolving Skyline: New Architectural Marvels
content:
Calgary, long recognized for its iconic Saddledome and panoramic Rocky Mountain backdrop, is entering a new era of architectural ambition. In recent years, the city has seen a surge in projects that not only aim to elevate the skyline but also redefine the way residents and visitors experience the urban core.

Among the standout additions is Telus Sky, a mixed-use tower that combines striking curves with integrated LED public art, making it one of Canada’s most visually captivating buildings. The Brookfield Place East Tower, Calgary’s tallest structure, continues to anchor the downtown financial district while setting new standards for sustainability and energy efficiency.

Cultural projects are also leaving their mark. The Calgary Central Library, with its dramatic wooden archway and glass façade, has become a global example of modern public space design. Meanwhile, new residential high-rises such as The Royal and Park Central are adding vibrancy to Beltline and inner-city neighborhoods, encouraging walkable lifestyles and community connection.

The shift isn’t just vertical — developers are increasingly embracing green building practices, integrating rooftop gardens, solar energy systems, and spaces for public art. This forward-thinking approach reflects Calgary’s goal of positioning itself as both an economic powerhouse and a leader in urban livability.

With more projects on the horizon — including mixed-use developments along the Bow River and innovative transit-oriented hubs — Calgary’s skyline is poised to tell a story of renewal, resilience, and world-class design for decades to come.
excerpt: Calgary’s skyline is transforming at an unprecedented pace, with striking new towers and bold design concepts redefining the city’s urban profile. From sustainable skyscrapers to cultural landmarks, the latest wave of development is shaping a future that blends innovation with Calgary’s unique character.
author: James Johnson

title: Calgary's Cultural Renaissance
content:
Calgary’s Cultural Renaissance

More than oil and office towers — this city’s got soul now

Walk through Calgary today and you’ll feel something shifting. It’s not just the skyline expanding — it’s the rhythm of the city itself. What was once written off as a buttoned-up oil town has been quietly, and now undeniably, finding its creative fire.

Call it a comeback, a glow-up, or a full-blown cultural renaissance. Whatever it is, it’s real — and it’s everywhere.

From Stampede to Street Art

Sure, the Stampede is still Calgary’s big, bold centerpiece — but now, it’s just one thread in a much bigger, more colorful tapestry. Murals are transforming blank walls into landmarks. Indie galleries like Contemporary Calgary are drawing attention beyond the usual art crowd. Even alleyways and light posts feel curated, buzzing with the kind of energy that doesn’t need a corporate sponsor to feel legit.

Walk 17th Ave or Inglewood, and you’ll catch buskers, pop-ups, and poetry on café chalkboards. Culture here doesn’t sit behind velvet ropes anymore — it spills onto the street.

Local Food with Real Roots

Calgary’s food scene isn’t just “pretty good for Alberta” anymore. It’s excellent — and fiercely local. Restaurants like Major Tom, D.O.P., and Nupo aren’t just catching up to other cities; they’re pushing things forward in their own lane.

What makes it different? Calgary chefs are telling stories. Menus now feature bison tartare, foraged prairie herbs, bannock bread, and small-batch everything. It’s regional without being gimmicky. It’s confident. And yeah — it tastes incredible.

Indigenous Voices Leading the Way

One of the most exciting (and overdue) parts of Calgary’s cultural rise is the amplification of Indigenous creators. From art installations and theater performances to Blackfoot language projects and land-based storytelling, Indigenous voices are not only being included — they’re leading.

Take the incredible work happening at the Making Treaty 7 Cultural Society, or the increasing visibility of artists like Lauren Crazybull. This isn’t about checking boxes — it’s about a city listening, learning, and beginning to honor where it sits.

Music, Film, and DIY Everything

Need proof that Calgary’s cultural core is alive? Just drop into Sled Island — the annual music and arts festival that now feels more essential than ever. Or check out the indie film scene bubbling up thanks to organizations like Calgary Underground Film Festival and CIFF.

Even the techy side of things is shifting. Places like Platform Calgary are becoming breeding grounds for creatives and coders alike, where innovation isn’t just profitable — it’s purposeful.

There’s also a rise in DIY collectives, art markets, and small-run zines. It’s messy, passionate, grassroots — and that’s what makes it worth paying attention to.

More Than a Boom-Bust Town

For decades, Calgary’s identity swung with oil prices. But today, there’s something sturdier, something deeper growing. A sense of place. A sense of possibility.

Is the cultural shift finished? Not even close. But that’s kind of the point. This renaissance isn’t about arriving — it’s about building. Together. With murals, menus, music, and stories that sound like home.

So if you haven’t looked at Calgary lately — really looked — it might be time. There’s a new beat playing under the cowboy hat.

And it’s loud.
excerpt: Explore Calgary's dynamic arts scene and cultural transformation in the heart of the Canadian Rockies.
